article.headline: Wyoming 69, Alabama State 54
article.story: LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- It may be that Steve Leven just needed the regular season to begin to find his stride. Leven scored 17 points to lead Wyoming to a 69-54 win over Alabama State in Sunday's first round of the Black Coaches Association Invitational. He scored 6 and 7 points in the Cowboys (1-0) two exhibition games heading into the tournament. "You don't want to say you don't care about exhibition games," he said. "But it's a different intensity when it comes to the beginning of the season." Coach Steve McClain said Leven shot the ball when he needed to. "I think he walked out of here feeling better than he did about his two exhibition games." The Cowboys next play North Carolina-Wilmington, which beat Butler 75-59 in the first round. Justin Williams added 11 points and 13 rebounds for Wyoming, which dominated for all but the first few minutes. The Hornets (0-1) had an 11-0 run late in the game but came no closer than 64-51. Alabama State coach Lewis Jackson blamed turnovers, pointing out that Wyoming had 50 rebounds to the Hornets' 34. "They came hard and we kind of shot ourselves in the foot," he said. In the second half, Wyoming led by as much as 62-39 on a basket by Williams and 2-of-2 free throws by Brad Jones, who finished with 10 points. The Hornets led 13-10 early, but Wyoming took control with a 9-0 run that included a 3-pointer by James Ebert and a breakaway basket by Leven. "When we finally got to pressing and got the tempo going, we played better," McClain said. The Hornets fought back to within 19-17 on baskets by Richard Lott and Akeim Claborn, but another Cowboys run -- this time 7-0 -- put them up 26-17. By halftime, that lead was 37-23. Alabama State was led by Claborn, who had 19 points and 10 rebounds before fouling out. Alexander Oliver followed up with nine points. This was Williams' first game since he sprained his knee in practice last month. He led the Mountain West Conference in blocked shots last year and on Sunday he had three. "I'm not looking to come in and be the lead scorer and superstar of the team," he said. But Wyoming will have to make do without another key player, Derek Wabbington, who was knocked over in the first half and left with a knee sprain. McClain said Wabbington would likely miss the next week and a half.
